NOTES_HAGGAI = {
    1: {
        1: 'HISTORICAL: The date "second year of Darius" fixes this oracle precisely to August 29, 520 BC, making Haggai among the most precisely datable texts in all Scripture. Darius I (Hystaspes) had recently consolidated Persian power after the upheavals following Cambyses\' death. Zerubbabel as "governor" (peha) reflects Judah\'s status as a Persian sub-province (Yehud), while the presence of a high priest alongside a Davidic governor reflects the dual leadership structure of the restoration community. (Ezra 3:2; Zech 4:6-14)',
        2: 'HEBREW: "YHWH of hosts" translates YHWH tseva\'ot (Strong\'s H6635), a divine title appearing over 250 times in the OT and concentrated heavily in the prophets. Tseva\'ot ("armies" or "hosts") likely refers to the divine council and celestial armies over which YHWH presides as sovereign. The people\'s rationalization — "the time has not come" — reflects spiritual torpor cloaked in pragmatic language, a pattern the prophets consistently confront. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The title YHWH tseva\'ot invokes YHWH\'s role as commander of heavenly armies, situating the rebuilding of the Temple within a cosmic, not merely political, frame. (Ps 82:1; Isa 6:3; 1 Kgs 22:19)',
        4: 'THEOLOGICAL: The word "paneled" (sefunim, from saphan, Strong\'s H5603) refers to costly cedar-lined interiors, the same material used in Solomon\'s Temple (1 Kgs 6:9). The contrast is devastating: the people lavish on their own dwellings the very resources appropriate to YHWH\'s house. This verse exposes a disordered theology of worship in which human comfort is prioritized over divine habitation. Covenantally, the Temple was the locus of YHWH\'s glory-presence (shekinah) among his people; its ruin signals a broken covenant relationship. (Ps 132:3-5; 2 Sam 7:2)',
        8: 'HEBREW: "That I may be glorified" renders the Niphal of kavad (Strong\'s H3513), meaning to be honored, weighty, or glorified. Kavod ("glory") is the same root as the visible manifestation of YHWH\'s presence that filled the Tabernacle (Exod 40:34) and Solomon\'s Temple (1 Kgs 8:11). TYPOLOGY: The call to build a house for YHWH\'s glory anticipates the NT revelation that YHWH\'s glory ultimately dwelt not in a stone edifice but in the incarnate Son (John 1:14, "the Word became flesh and tabernacled among us, and we beheld his glory"). The rebuilt Temple is thus a typological waystation pointing to the true Temple. (John 2:19-21; Rev 21:22)',
        12: 'THEOLOGICAL: The threefold response — obedience of leaders, obedience of the remnant, and fear before YHWH — mirrors the covenant renewal pattern found throughout Deuteronomy and the Former Prophets. The word "remnant" (she\'erit, Strong\'s H7611) is a theologically loaded term, evoking Isaiah\'s and Micah\'s theology of a faithful surviving core through whom YHWH would fulfill his promises. The people\'s fear (yare\', Strong\'s H3372) before YHWH is not panic but the covenant reverence that is the beginning of wisdom (Prov 1:7). (Isa 10:20-22; Mic 5:7-8; Ezra 5:1-2)',
        13: 'HEBREW: Haggai is called "the messenger of YHWH" (mal\'ak YHWH, Strong\'s H4397), the same term used for angelic messengers and theophanies throughout the OT. This is the only place in the Hebrew prophets where a prophet is explicitly designated by this title, blurring the boundary between prophetic and angelic function and underscoring the divine authority of his message. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The mal\'ak YHWH language situates the prophet within the divine council\'s communication structure — a heavenly herald bearing the King\'s decree to earth. (Isa 6:8; Mal 3:1; Rev 1:1)',
        14: 'THEOLOGICAL: "YHWH stirred up the spirit (ruach)" employs the Piel of \'ur (Strong\'s H5782), meaning to rouse, awaken, or incite. This divine awakening of the ruach (spirit, Strong\'s H7307) of both civil and religious leaders demonstrates that the restoration project is not merely a human political achievement but a sovereign act of YHWH. TYPOLOGY: The stirring of Zerubbabel\'s ruach prefigures the eschatological outpouring of the Spirit upon God\'s people (Joel 2:28-29; Acts 2), and Zerubbabel himself is a Davidic type pointing toward the greater Son of David who would build the true Temple of God. (Zech 4:6-9; Matt 1:12-13; Eph 2:21-22)',
        15: 'HISTORICAL: The date "twenty-fourth day of the sixth month" (approximately September 21, 520 BC) indicates that work on the Temple resumed only twenty-three days after Haggai\'s initial oracle. This rapid response testifies to the effectiveness of prophetic preaching when accompanied by the sovereign work of YHWH\'s Spirit (v. 14). The precision of dating throughout Haggai (cf. 2:1, 10, 20) reflects both scribal care and the prophet\'s conviction that YHWH acts concretely within historical time. (Ezra 5:1-2; Zech 1:1)',
    },
    2: {
        3: 'HISTORICAL: The question "who saw this house in its former glory?" implies that elderly returnees (cf. Ezra 3:12) could recall Solomon\'s temple destroyed in 586 BC, some 66 years prior. The contrast between past splendor and present modest foundations produced public mourning. This rhetorical question sets up YHWH\'s counter-promise in vv. 6-9.',
        4: 'HEBREW: "Chazaq" (Strong\'s H2388) — "be strong, take courage" — appears three times in rapid succession, once for each addressee (governor, priest, people), forming a triple charge mirroring Joshua\'s commissioning (Josh 1:6-9). The phrase "I am with you" (ani ittkem) is the foundational covenant assurance echoing the Immanuel motif.',
        5: 'THEOLOGICAL: The phrase "according to the word I cut (karath) with you" recalls the Mosaic covenant; the verb karath ("to cut") is the standard covenant-making term, alluding to the sacrificial rite of covenant ratification. The continuing presence of the ruach (Spirit) in the community\'s midst anticipates the new covenant promise of the Spirit\'s indwelling (Ezek 36:27; Joel 2:28).',
        6: 'THEOLOGICAL: The cosmic shaking of heavens, earth, sea, and dry land echoes theophanic language of Sinai (Exod 19:18; Ps 68:8) and anticipates eschatological judgment. The writer of Hebrews (12:26-27) cites this verse explicitly, interpreting the shaking as the removal of the old order to establish the unshakable kingdom of the Messiah.',
        7: 'HEBREW: "Chemdah" (Strong\'s H2532) — "desire, treasure, precious thing" — is rendered in the singular collective. Some traditions (following the Vulgate\'s "Desideratus cunctis gentibus") interpreted this as a messianic title ("the Desired of all nations"), though the Hebrew verb "shall come" is plural, suggesting nations rather than a person. Nonetheless, the passage was broadly received as anticipating the Messiah\'s advent filling the Second Temple with his presence (Mal 3:1; Luke 2:22-38). TYPOLOGY: Jesus\' presentation and ministry at the Second Temple (Luke 2; John 2) fulfills the promise that YHWH\'s glory would fill this very structure, greater than the Shekinah of the Solomonic house.',
        9: 'THEOLOGICAL: The "latter glory" (kabod ha-acharon) greater than the former is the theological apex of the book. The shalom YHWH promises "in this place" is not merely the cessation of conflict but the fullness of covenantal well-being. TYPOLOGY: Christian interpretation identifies the fulfillment in the incarnate Word entering the Second Temple precincts (John 2:13-22; Matt 21:12-16), bringing the true Shekinah in flesh (John 1:14), and ultimately establishing eschatological shalom through his atoning work.',
        11: 'HEBREW: "Torah" here is used in the technical priestly sense of "ruling" or "instruction" (Strong\'s H8451), not simply "law." The priests served as halakhic arbiters in cultic matters (Deut 17:8-13; Lev 10:10-11). The use of a priestly torah-inquiry as a parabolic device is notable rhetorical strategy.',
        14: 'THEOLOGICAL: YHWH declares the people and their offerings ritually unclean because unholiness communicates more readily than holiness — a principle illustrated by the priestly ruling of vv. 12-13. This indicts not the rebuilding effort itself but the prior years of self-focused neglect (cf. Hag 1:4-6). The corruption of worship taints the entire agricultural economy, reversing covenant blessing.',
        17: 'HISTORICAL: The agricultural curses of blight (shiddaphon), mildew (yerakon), and hail recall the covenant curse-lists of Deuteronomy (28:22) and parallel ANE treaty-curse formulae in which the suzerain deity withdraws blessing from a disloyal vassal. The indictment "you did not turn to me" (ve-lo-shavtem aday) echoes the prophetic refrain in Amos 4:6-11, likely a deliberate intertextual link.',
        22: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: The overthrowing of thrones and kingdoms employs cosmic-warfare language resonant with divine council theology. The "throne of kingdoms" represents both earthly imperial powers and, in Second Temple cosmology, the heavenly patrons (sons of God) who stand behind them (cf. Deut 32:8; Dan 10:13, 20). YHWH\'s shaking removes both the human structures and their supernatural backing, establishing his own universal sovereignty.',
        23: 'TYPOLOGY: The signet ring (chotam, Strong\'s H2368) is the image of intimate authority and royal identity — the instrument by which a king authenticates decrees. Significantly, Zerubbabel\'s ancestor Jeconiah (Coniah) was declared by YHWH to be "torn off" like a signet ring (Jer 22:24), a curse now reversed in his grandson. This reversal is christologically loaded: Matthew\'s genealogy (1:12) traces the Davidic line through Zerubbabel to Jesus, in whom the signet-ring promise is ultimately fulfilled — the one who bears the Father\'s full authority and image (Heb 1:3; John 14:9). THEOLOGICAL: The closing "I have chosen you" (ki-vekha bacharti) is election language of the highest order, recalling the Davidic covenant (Ps 89:3-4) and pointing forward to the Chosen Servant of Isaiah (42:1), whose identity converges in the Messiah.',
    },
}